item.content:encoded:
Immutable systems offer many benefits—until you need to customize your filesystem by installing packages. While installing software isn’t difficult per se, SteamOS’s design means that most customizations are wiped during system upgrades. About a year ago, Valve added  to the list of directories that remain intact during updates, and that’s where Nix stores all of its packages.If you’re not familiar with Nix: it’s a package manager that uses declarative definitions for your software instead of commands like  or . You simply list all your desired packages in a configuration file, and Nix takes care of installing them. Additionally, the handy  utility lets you spawn temporary shells with the packages you specify.There are two primary ways to work with Nix comfortably: you can either run NixOS (which isn’t ideal on a Steam Deck) or use Home Manager.sh <(curl -L https://nixos.org/nix/install) --no-daemonThis command installs Nix in single-user mode (), which is a good fit for SteamOS since it may not require  for most operations. (If it does ask for sudo, you’ll need to set up sudo on your Steam Deck.)Next, load Nix into your current terminal session:By default, Nix uses the unstable branch of packages. To switch to the stable channel, run:nix-channel --add https://nixos.org/channels/nixos-24.11 nixpkgsThis command sets your  channel to the latest stable version (in this example, 24.11). In the future, check the current stable version on the NixOS homepage.Nix is now installed—but without Home Manager, it isn’t very user-friendly.First, add the Home Manager channel to your Nix configuration:nix-channel --add https://github.com/nix-community/home-manager/archive/release-24.11.tar.gz home-manager Ensure that the version for both Nix and Home Manager match. In this example, both are 24.11.If you prefer the unstable branch, you can instead run: nix-channel --add https://github.com/nix-community/home-manager/archive/master.tar.gz home-managerUpdate your channels to include these changes:Before proceeding, back up your Bash configuration files:mv .bash_profile .bash_profile.bckpIf you choose not to back them up, you’ll need to remove them because Home Manager creates these files during installation and will fail if they already exist.Now, run the Home Manager installation:nix-shell '<home-manager>' -A installOnce the installation completes, create your Home Manager configuration file using a text editor:kate ~/.config/home-manager/home.nixPaste in the following configuration:{ config, pkgs, ... }:
{
  home.username = "deck";
  home.homeDirectory = "/home/deck";

  programs.bash = {
    enable = true;
    initExtra = ''
      if [ -e $HOME/.nix-profile/etc/profile.d/nix.sh ]; then . $HOME/.nix-profile/etc/profile.d/nix.sh; fi

      export NIX_SHELL_PRESERVE_PROMPT=1
      if [[ -n "$IN_NIX_SHELL" ]]; then
        export PS1="$PS1(nix-shell) "
      fi
    '';
  };

  home.stateVersion = "24.11"; # don't change this even if you upgrade your channel in the future, this should stay the same as the version you first installed nix on

  home.packages = with pkgs; [

  ];

  programs.home-manager.enable = true;
}This configuration does the following:Sets your username to  (the default on Steam Deck).Specifies the correct path to your home directory.Enables Home Manager to manage your Bash shell and ensures the Nix environment is loaded automatically—so you won’t have to source it manually each time.Adds a  suffix to your terminal prompt when you’re in a Nix shell, which is a subtle but useful improvement over the default behavior.Defines the , which should remain the same as when you first installed Nix (even if you later change your channels). You should never change it after the initial Nix installationEnables Home Manager itself.Provides an empty list () where you can later add your desired packages.Apply your new configuration by running:This is the basic workflow for managing your environment with Nix: update your configuration file and then run  to apply the changes.After closing and reopening your terminal, test the setup by running . If you see an error indicating that  is missing, everything is working as expected. (If the command isn’t found at all, something went wrong.)To install packages, simply add them to the  list in your configuration file. For example, to install  (for network scanning) and  (because a cow makes everything better), update your configuration as follows:  home.packages = with pkgs; [
      nmap
      cowsay
  ];Keep the rest of the file unchanged, then apply the new configuration with . You can test the setup by running:echo "Hello from my Steam Deck!" | cowsayYou should see this beauty in your terminal: ___________________________ 
< Hello from my Steam Deck! >
 --------------------------- 
        \   ^__^
         \  (oo)\_______
            (__)\       )\/\
                ||----w |
                ||     ||
Running  should display its usage instructions. If you decide to remove  (you're keeping , right?), just delete it from the configuration file and run  again.Create a desktop shortcut to your configuration file:
	ln -s ~/.config/home-manager/home.nix ~/Desktop/Nix_ConfigRun  periodically to remove unused packages and free up space.Install the  package. This nifty tool lets you run any package on the fly by simply prefixing the command with a comma.
	For example, instead of adding  to your configuration, you could run  to temporarily use it. (notice the comma in front of nmap)Nix can do much more than just manage packages—for instance, you can use it to create environment variables, shell aliases, systemd services, files, and more.
